    rationale: "In a sexually active young adult with monoarticular or oligoarticular arthritis, fever, and urogenital symptoms, gonococcal (disseminated gonococcal infection) arthritis is the most likely diagnosis. Age under 60 shifts the differential toward infectious and crystal-induced arthritis rather than osteoarthritis. Polymyalgia rheumatica occurs in patients over 60. Pseudogout is more common in older adults and typically affects the knee or wrist without urogenital symptoms. Osteoarthritis is degenerative and does not cause fever.",
