    selectCount: 3,
    rationale: "Secondary osteoporosis results from conditions that impair bone formation or accelerate bone resorption. Thyrotoxicosis increases bone turnover and resorption via excess thyroid hormone. Celiac disease causes malabsorption of calcium and vitamin D, impairing bone mineralization. Chronic renal disease causes renal osteodystrophy through impaired vitamin D activation and secondary hyperparathyroidism. Hypothyroidism does not cause osteoporosis \u2014 it is associated with decreased bone turnover. Obesity is actually protective against osteoporosis due to increased mechanical loading and higher estrogen levels from adipose tissue.",
