    rationale: "Corticosteroids suppress osteoblast differentiation and function (reducing bone formation) while simultaneously promoting osteoclast activity (increasing bone resorption). This dual mechanism creates a net loss of bone mineral density. While corticosteroids do impair intestinal calcium absorption and can trigger secondary hyperparathyroidism, the direct cellular effects on osteoblast inhibition and osteoclast stimulation are the primary drivers of steroid-induced osteoporosis. Option B reverses the osteoclast effect incorrectly. Option C is incomplete. Option D describes a secondary mechanism, not the primary one.",
