    rationale: "Sacroiliac joint pain typically refers to the buttock and posterior thigh but rarely extends below the knee. True lumbar radiculopathy (nerve root compression) characteristically radiates in a dermatomal pattern that extends to the foot (e.g., L5 radiculopathy causes pain to the dorsum of the foot; S1 to the lateral foot and heel). This distinction helps differentiate SI joint pathology from disc herniation. Sacroiliac pain can be unilateral or bilateral. The straight leg raise tests for lumbar nerve root tension, not SI joint pathology. Neurological deficits (weakness, sensory loss, reflex changes) are features of radiculopathy, not sacroiliitis.",
