    rationale: "Quadriceps atrophy in chronic knee disease results from arthrogenic muscle inhibition \u2014 persistent nociceptive and mechanoreceptor input from the joint reflexively suppresses alpha motor neuron activity to the quadriceps, leading to disuse atrophy even without direct nerve injury. This is a well-recognized phenomenon in chronic effusion and pain states. Femoral artery compression (B) would cause ischemic symptoms, not isolated muscle wasting. Patellar tendon rupture (C) causes acute loss of extension, not gradual atrophy. Tibial nerve compression (D) would affect plantar flexion and foot intrinsics, not the quadriceps.",
